Question: Design a Java program to model race cars using object-oriented
programming.
a. Make an abstract class called RaceCar that stores each car’s model
name and engine power. Make the engine power as a private field and
add an abstract method called displayInfo(), which will print the car's
details.
b. Create two subclasses, FormulaCar and Sports Car, that extend
RaceCar and implement the displayInfo() method to show the model
name and engine power
c. Create one FormulaCar and one SportsCar object with different
model names and engine powers
d. Call their displayInfo() method within main function to show each
car’s details

Ans:
(a) 
abstract class RaceCar{
String modelName;
private int enginePower;
RaceCar(String modelName, int enginePower){
this.modelName = modelName;
this.enginePower = enginePower;
}
public int getEnginePower(){
return enginePower;
}
abstract void displayInfo();
}

(b) 
class FormulaCar extends RaceCar{
FormulaCar (String modelName, int enginePower){
super(modelName, enginePower);
}
void displayInfo(){
System.out.println("Formula Car Model:"+ modelName);
System.out.println("Engine Power:"+ getEnginePower()+"HP");
}
}
class SportsCar extends RaceCar{
SportsCar (String modelName, int enginePower){
super(modelName, enginePower);
}
void displayInfo(){
System.out.println("Sports Car Model:"+ modelName);
System.out.println("Engine Power:"+ getEnginePower()+"HP");
}
}

(c)
FormulaCar f1 = new FormulaCar("Ferrari F1",1000);
SportsCar S1 = new SportsCar("Lamborghini Aventador",750);

(d)
